    <!-- THE QUESTION -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">01 /</span>THE QUESTION ON YOUR BALLOT
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        Read it carefully. <span class="red"
          >They're counting on you not to.</span
        >
      </h2>
      <p class="section-deck">
        Every word of a ballot question is a fight. This one was written by the
        people who drew the 10-1 map — and they spent their word budget on
        exactly two moves.
      </p>

      <div class="ballot">
        <p class="ballot-text">
          "Should the Constitution of Virginia be amended to allow the General
          Assembly to <span class="flag-gold">temporarily</span> adopt new congressional
          districts to
          <span class="flag">restore fairness</span> in the upcoming elections, while
          ensuring Virginia's standard redistricting process resumes for all future
          redistricting after the 2030 census?"
        </p>
        <div class="ballot-meta">
          VA DEPT. OF ELECTIONS — PROPOSED AMENDMENT, APRIL 2026 SPECIAL
          ELECTION
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Notice what's <strong>not</strong> on the ballot: the actual map. The proposed
          10-1 district layout does not appear in the question you are being asked
          to vote on. You are voting on the
          <em>power to draw it</em>, not the map itself — which means a yes vote
          is a blank check.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="annot">
        <div class="annot-word">"restore fairness"</div>
        <div class="annot-text">
          <strong>The load-bearing phrase.</strong> Presented as a correction. In
          practice, it means handing one party 91% of Virginia's House delegation
          in a state that splits almost evenly in statewide races. The word "fair"
          does not appear anywhere in the map itself — only in the ballot language
          asking permission to draw it.
        </div>
        <div class="annot-word gold">"temporarily"</div>
        <div class="annot-text">
          <strong>Until 2031.</strong> Which is three federal elections, every House
          seat up for grabs. "Temporary" doing a lot of work when the timeline covers
          100% of the next decade's congressional cycle.
        </div>
        <div class="annot-word">"upcoming elections"</div>
        <div class="annot-text">
          <strong>No limit on scope.</strong> The General Assembly gets to pick the
          map. You get to vote on whether they get to pick.
        </div>
        <div class="annot-word gold">"standard … process resumes"</div>
        <div class="annot-text">
          <strong>The permission slip.</strong> Framed as a return-to-normal after
          a one-time intervention. What it actually does is carve a retaliation loophole
          into the Virginia Constitution that any future legislature can invoke the
          moment another state redraws.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- THE MAP -->
    <section class="section section-wide">
