    <!-- THE CASE FOR NO -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-label">
        <span class="num">07 /</span>THE CASE FOR NO
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-title">
        Five reasons this amendment fails its
        <span class="red">own stated test.</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="case">
        <div class="case-item">
          <div class="case-num">01</div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <h3>
              It is a partisan gerrymander dressed up as a fairness measure.
            </h3>
            <p>
              Virginia splits roughly <strong>54/46</strong> in statewide races. A
              "fair" outcome is somewhere in the neighborhood of a 6–5 split. The
              proposed map delivers <strong>10–1</strong>. That isn't a
              correction. That's a takeover.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-item">
          <div class="case-num">02</div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <h3>Two wrongs don't make a right.</h3>
            <p>
              The stated justification is <strong>Texas</strong> — that other states
              redrew first, so Virginia has to respond. Gerrymandering is bad when
              Republicans do it <strong>and</strong> when Democrats do it. An amendment
              that embraces the logic of the thing you claim to oppose is not principled
              — it's tit-for-tat.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-item">
          <div class="case-num">03</div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <h3>It guts the redistricting commission Virginians voted for.</h3>
            <p>
              In <strong>2020</strong>, Virginia voters approved — by a
              two-thirds majority — a constitutional amendment taking map
              drawing away from the General Assembly and giving it to an
              independent bipartisan commission. This amendment
              <strong>overrides that decision</strong> for the entire rest of the
              decade. You're being asked to unvote your own 2020 vote.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-item">
          <div class="case-num">04</div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <h3>It erases the only competitive House seats Virginia has.</h3>
            <p>
              VA-2 and VA-7 are among the
              <strong>most competitive districts in the country</strong>. That's
              good for voters — it means candidates have to fight for votes, and
              incumbents can actually lose. The new map doesn't just flip them.
              It <strong>eliminates competition</strong>
              altogether.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="case-item">
          <div class="case-num">05</div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <h3>It sets a permanent mid-decade gerrymander precedent.</h3>
            <p>
              The amendment's trigger ("if another state redraws") creates a
              <strong>cycle with no exit</strong>. Every future GOP or
              Democratic legislature in any state can force every other state to
              respond. Redistricting stops happening once a decade and starts
              happening <strong>every election</strong>. The big loser is the
              voter.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

